                            	   118: *******************************************************************
                            	   119: *
                            	   120: * *** Tables *** DIRECT *** EXEC ***
                            	   121: *
                            	   122: * This section of the code tests a string against a table. When
                            	   123: * a match is found, control is transferred to the section of
                            	   124: * code according to the table.
                            	   125: *
                            	   126: * At 'EXEC', A0 should point to the string, A1 should point to
                            	   127: * the character table, and A2 should point to the execution
                            	   128: * table. At 'DIRECT', A0 should point to the string, A1 and
                            	   129: * A2 will be set up to point to TAB1 and TAB1.1, which are
                            	   130: * the tables of all direct and statement commands.
                            	   131: *
                            	   132: * A '.' in the string will terminate the test and the partial
                            	   133: * match will be considered as a match, e.g. 'P.', 'PR.','PRI.',
                            	   134: * 'PRIN.', or 'PRINT' will all match 'PRINT'.
                            	   135: *
                            	   136: * There are two tables: the character table and the execution
                            	   137: * table. The character table consists of any number of text items.
                            	   138: * Each item is a string of characters with the last character's
                            	   139: * high bit set to one. The execution table holds a 16-bit
                            	   140: * execution addresses that correspond to each entry in the
                            	   141: * character table.
                            	   142: *
                            	   143: * The end of the character table is a 0 byte which corresponds
                            	   144: * to the default routine in the execution table, which is
                            	   145: * executed if none of the other table items are matched.
                            	   146: *
                            	   147: * Character-matching tables:
